'''Makimuku Yadzuka Kofun''' (纒向矢塚古墳) is a keyhole-shaped {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun}}  found on the premises of [[Makimuku ruins]]<ref>https://www.rekihaku.ac.jp/english/outline/publication/ronbun/ronbun7/pdf/163004.pdf</ref>.<ref>{{Cite web|title=「纒,向,矢,塚,古墳,まき,むく,づか,奈良,県,桜井,市,群,属する」を使った英語表現・例文・フレーズ｜Cheer up! English|url=http://english.cheerup.jp/corpus/search?name=%E7%BA%92+%E5%90%91+%E7%9F%A2+%E5%A1%9A+%E5%8F%A4%E5%A2%B3+%E3%81%BE%E3%81%8D+%E3%82%80%E3%81%8F+%E3%81%A5%E3%81%8B+%E5%A5%88%E8%89%AF+%E7%9C%8C+%E6%A1%9C%E4%BA%95+%E5%B8%82+%E7%BE%A4+%E5%B1%9E%E3%81%99%E3%82%8B|access-date=2023-10-16|website=Cheer up! English|language=ja}}</ref> It is a member of the {{ill|Makimuku Kofun Group|ja|纒向古墳群}}, located in {{ill|Sakurai, Nara|ja|桜井市}}, Nara Prefecture, Japan.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kidder|first=J. Edward|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9780824862848|title=Himiko and Japan's Elusive Chiefdom of Yamatai|date=2017-12-18|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=978-0-8248-6284-8}}</ref>{{rp|249}} 

{{ill|Higashidaotsuka Kofun|lt=Higaida-ōtsuka Kofun|ja|東田大塚古墳|1=Higaida Ōtsuka Kofun|lt=Higaida Ōtsuka Kofun}} is located to the north of it..<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|last=Kidder|first=J. Edward|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9780824862848|title=Himiko and Japan's Elusive Chiefdom of Yamatai|date=2017-12-18|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=978-0-8248-6284-8}}</ref>{{rp|251}}It's on the northwestern part of the group..<ref name=":1" />{{rp|251}}

On January 26, 2006, it was Historic Site1 as a National Historic Site as part of the Makimuku Kofun Cluster.

== Overview ==

* '''location:''' Higashida, Sakurai City, Nara Prefecture
* '''Interred_individual:''' Unknown
* '''built:''' Early Kofun period (mid-3rd century or earlier) <ref name=Makimukugaku>{{Cite web|url=http://www.city.sakurai.nara.jp/maki_c/info/iseki.html|title=What is the Makimuku Site?|publisher=Sakurai City Makimuku Research Center|accessdate=2013-05-04}}</ref>
* '''type:''' {{ill|Makimuku-style keyhole-shaped tumulus|ja|纒向型前方後円墳}} (no stone facing or {{ill|haniwa|ja|埴輪}})<ref name=Makimukugaku/>
* '''area:'''
** Overall length: approx. 96 meters (at least 93 meters)<ref name=Wakazakura235>{{Cite web|url=http://www.city.sakurai.nara.jp/bunkazai/bunkazai12.html|title=Fieldwork Reports (235th): Confirmation Survey of Yadzuka Kofun|publisher=Sakurai City ("Wakazakura" Newsletter, July 2008)|accessdate=2013-05-05}}</ref>
** Rear mound diameter: approx. 64 meters (east-west: approx. 64 meters; north-south: approx. 56 meters)
** Rear mound height: 5 meters
** Front mound length: 32 meters (current length: approx. 28 meters<ref name=Wakazakura235/>)
** Moat width: 17–23 meters; depth: approx. 0.6 meters<ref name=Makimukugaku/>
* '''burial:''' Uninvestigated
** Stone slabs visible at the top suggest the presence of either a {{ill|vertical stone chamber|ja|竪穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=竪穴式石室|4=zh|5=豎穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber}} or a {{ill|Hakogata sekkan (box-shaped stone coffin)|lt=Hakogata sekkan|ja|箱式石棺}}.

== burial goods ==

burial goods from the site include:
* {{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery}} (Makimuku III period)
* Pottery fragments

